	(4, 9, 'Introduction', 'text', 'Learn how fires start, spread, and behave in residential and community settings.', NULL, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2026-07-09 04:19:46', '2026-07-09 04:19:46'),
	(5, 10, 'Evacuation Guide', 'text', 'Step-by-step guide for safe evacuation during fire emergencies.', NULL, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2026-07-09 04:19:46', '2026-07-09 04:19:46'),
	(6, 11, 'Flood Advisory Basics', 'text', 'How to interpret PAGASA and local flood warning levels.', NULL, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, 'How to interpret PAGASA and local flood warning levels.', 'ready', NULL, '2026-07-10 09:37:42', '2026-07-09 04:19:46', '2026-07-10 09:37:42'),
	(7, 12, 'Earthquake Drill Steps', 'text', 'Practice the correct drop-cover-hold technique during seismic events.', NULL, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, 'Practice the correct drop-cover-hold technique during seismic events.', 'ready', NULL, '2026-07-09 15:04:21', '2026-07-09 04:19:46', '2026-07-09 15:04:21'),
	(8, 15, 'Training Content', 'text', '<h2><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:18pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;">Fire Safety and Emergency Response<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:13.5pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;">Lesson 3: Fire Prevention<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:10.5293pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;">Overview<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">Fire prevention is the practice of identifying and eliminating potential fire hazards before they cause<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">damage or injury. While emergency response is important, preventing a fire from occurring is the most<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">effective way to protect lives, property, and the environment. Everyone has a responsibility to follow safe<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">practices at home, in schools, workplaces, and public facilities.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:18pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;">Learning Objectives<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">At the end of this lesson, participants should be able to:<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Identify common fire hazards.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Apply fire prevention practices in daily activities.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Maintain a safe environment at home and in the workplace.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Recognize the importance of regular fire safety inspections.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:18pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;">What is Fire Prevention?<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">Fire prevention refers to the actions taken to reduce the risk of fire by eliminating hazards and promoting<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">safe practices. Many fire incidents can be avoided through proper awareness, responsible behavior, and<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">regular safety inspections.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:18pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;">Common Fire Prevention Practices<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:13.5pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;">1. Electrical Safety<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">Electrical faults are one of the leading causes of fire incidents.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">Best Practices:<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Do not overload electrical outlets.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Replace damaged electrical cords immediately.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Unplug appliances when not in use.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Have faulty wiring repaired by a qualified electrician.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(110,110,110);">1</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Avoid using damaged extension cords.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:13.5pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;">2. Safe Cooking Practices<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">Cooking is one of the most common sources of residential fires.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">Best Practices:<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Never leave cooking unattended.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Keep flammable materials away from the stove.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Turn off gas valves after cooking.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Keep children away from cooking areas.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Keep a fire extinguisher nearby.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:13.5pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;">3. Proper Storage of Flammable Materials<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">Flammable materials can easily ignite when exposed to heat or sparks.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">Examples:<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Gasoline<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• LPG cylinders<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Paint thinner<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Alcohol<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Aerosol cans<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">Best Practices:<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Store in cool, dry, and well-ventilated areas.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Keep away from open flames.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Follow manufacturer storage instructions.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Never store excessive amounts inside buildings.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:13.5pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;">4. Good Housekeeping<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">A clean and organized environment reduces fire hazards.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">Best Practices:<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Remove unnecessary combustible materials.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Dispose of trash regularly.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Keep exits and hallways free from obstructions.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(110,110,110);">2</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Store papers and cardboard away from heat sources.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:13.5pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;">5. Workplace Fire Safety<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">Employees should always follow workplace fire safety procedures.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">Best Practices:<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Know the location of fire extinguishers.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Identify emergency exits.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Participate in fire drills.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Report fire hazards immediately.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Follow all workplace safety policies.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:18pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;">Fire Prevention at Home<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">Homeowners and family members should:<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Install smoke alarms.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Test smoke alarms regularly.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Keep emergency contact numbers accessible.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Prepare a family evacuation plan.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Teach children basic fire safety.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:18pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;">Fire Prevention in Government Offices<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">Government facilities should:<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Conduct regular fire safety inspections.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Maintain fire extinguishers.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Keep evacuation routes clear.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Display emergency exit signs.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Train employees on emergency response procedures.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:18pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;">Fire Safety Checklist<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">Before leaving your home or workplace, always check the following:<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'FreeSans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">☐</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);"> Electrical appliances are turned off.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(110,110,110);">3</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'FreeSans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">☐</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);"> Gas valves are closed.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'FreeSans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">☐</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);"> Fire exits are unobstructed.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'FreeSans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">☐</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);"> Flammable materials are stored properly.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'FreeSans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">☐</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);"> Smoke detectors are functioning.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'FreeSans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">☐</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);"> Fire extinguishers are accessible.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:18pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;">Key Takeaways<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Most fire incidents are preventable.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Safe electrical practices significantly reduce fire risks.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Proper housekeeping helps eliminate fire hazards.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Everyone has a role in maintaining fire safety.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">• Prevention is always better than emergency response.<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:18pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;">Lesson Summary<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">Fire prevention begins with awareness and responsible behavior. By identifying hazards, following safety<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">procedures, and maintaining a clean and organized environment, individuals can greatly reduce the<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">likelihood of fire incidents. Consistent fire prevention practices help protect lives, property, and the<br>\r\n</span><span style="mso-spacerun:\'yes\';font-size:9pt;font-family:\'Noto Sans\';color:rgb(0,0,0);">community</span></h2>', NULL, NULL, 1, 3, 3, 'Fire Safety and Emergency Response Lesson 3: Fire Prevention Overview Fire prevention is the practice of identifying and eliminating potential fire hazards before they cause damage or injury. While emergency response is important, preventing a fire from occurring is the most effective way to protect lives, property, and the environment. Everyone has a responsibility to follow safe practices at home, in schools, workplaces, and public facilities. Learning Objectives At the end of this lesson, participants should be able to: • Identify common fire hazards. • Apply fire prevention practices in daily activities. • Maintain a safe environment at home and in the workplace. • Recognize the importance of regular fire safety inspections. What is Fire Prevention? Fire prevention refers to the actions taken to reduce the risk of fire by eliminating hazards and promoting safe practices. Many fire incidents can be avoided through proper awareness, responsible behavior, and regular safety inspections. Common Fire Prevention Practices 1. Electrical Safety Electrical faults are one of the leading causes of fire incidents. Best Practices: • Do not overload electrical outlets. • Replace damaged electrical cords immediately. • Unplug appliances when not in use. • Have faulty wiring repaired by a qualified electrician. 1• Avoid using damaged extension cords. 2. Safe Cooking Practices Cooking is one of the most common sources of residential fires. Best Practices: • Never leave cooking unattended. • Keep flammable materials away from the stove. • Turn off gas valves after cooking. • Keep children away from cooking areas. • Keep a fire extinguisher nearby. 3. Proper Storage of Flammable Materials Flammable materials can easily ignite when exposed to heat or sparks. Examples: • Gasoline • LPG cylinders • Paint thinner • Alcohol • Aerosol cans Best Practices: • Store in cool, dry, and well-ventilated areas. • Keep away from open flames. • Follow manufacturer storage instructions. • Never store excessive amounts inside buildings. 4. Good Housekeeping A clean and organized environment reduces fire hazards. Best Practices: • Remove unnecessary combustible materials. • Dispose of trash regularly. • Keep exits and hallways free from obstructions. 2• Store papers and cardboard away from heat sources. 5. Workplace Fire Safety Employees should always follow workplace fire safety procedures. Best Practices: • Know the location of fire extinguishers. • Identify emergency exits. • Participate in fire drills. • Report fire hazards immediately. • Follow all workplace safety policies. Fire Prevention at Home Homeowners and family members should: • Install smoke alarms. • Test smoke alarms regularly. • Keep emergency contact numbers accessible. • Prepare a family evacuation plan. • Teach children basic fire safety. Fire Prevention in Government Offices Government facilities should: • Conduct regular fire safety inspections. • Maintain fire extinguishers. • Keep evacuation routes clear. • Display emergency exit signs. • Train employees on emergency response procedures. Fire Safety Checklist Before leaving your home or workplace, always check the following: ☐ Electrical appliances are turned off. 3☐ Gas valves are closed. ☐ Fire exits are unobstructed. ☐ Flammable materials are stored properly. ☐ Smoke detectors are functioning. ☐ Fire extinguishers are accessible. Key Takeaways • Most fire incidents are preventable. • Safe electrical practices significantly reduce fire risks. • Proper housekeeping helps eliminate fire hazards. • Everyone has a role in maintaining fire safety. • Prevention is always better than emergency response. Lesson Summary Fire prevention begins with awareness and responsible behavior. By identifying hazards, following safety procedures, and maintaining a clean and organized environment, individuals can greatly reduce the likelihood of fire incidents. Consistent fire prevention practices help protect lives, property, and the community', 'ready', NULL, '2026-07-10 06:19:32', '2026-07-10 05:51:47', '2026-07-10 06:19:32'),
	(11, 15, 'Attachment 1', 'pdf', NULL, '/storage/training-contents/pdf/1lyh6x2Yw0BoC1euSQy6QDPFo0EWBAAO3qLy8P2v.pdf', NULL, 3, 3, 3, 'Fire Safety and Emergency Response Lesson 3: Fire Prevention Overview Fire prevention is the practice of identifying and eliminating potential fire hazards before they cause damage or injury. While emergency response is important, preventing a fire from occurring is the most effective way to protect lives, property, and the environment. Everyone has a responsibility to follow safe practices at home, in schools, workplaces, and public facilities. Learning Objectives At the end of this lesson, participants should be able to: Identify common fire hazards. Apply fire prevention practices in daily activities. Maintain a safe environment at home and in the workplace. Recognize the importance of regular fire safety inspections. What is Fire Prevention? Fire prevention refers to the actions taken to reduce the risk of fire by eliminating hazards and promoting safe practices. Many fire incidents can be avoided through proper awareness, responsible behavior, and regular safety inspections. Common Fire Prevention Practices 1. Electrical Safety Electrical faults are one of the leading causes of fire incidents. Best Practices: Do not overload electrical outlets. Replace damaged electrical cords immediately. Unplug appliances when not in use. Have faulty wiring repaired by a qualified electrician. • • • • • • • • 1 Avoid using damaged extension cords. 2. Safe Cooking Practices Cooking is one of the most common sources of residential fires. Best Practices: Never leave cooking unattended. Keep flammable materials away from the stove. Turn off gas valves after cooking. Keep children away from cooking areas. Keep a fire extinguisher nearby. 3. Proper Storage of Flammable Materials Flammable materials can easily ignite when exposed to heat or sparks. Examples: Gasoline LPG cylinders Paint thinner Alcohol Aerosol cans Best Practices: Store in cool, dry, and well-ventilated areas. Keep away from open flames. Follow manufacturer storage instructions. Never store excessive amounts inside buildings. 4. Good Housekeeping A clean and organized environment reduces fire hazards. Best Practices: Remove unnecessary combustible materials. Dispose of trash regularly. Keep exits and hallways free from obstructions. • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • 2 Store papers and cardboard away from heat sources. 5. Workplace Fire Safety Employees should always follow workplace fire safety procedures. Best Practices: Know the location of fire extinguishers. Identify emergency exits. Participate in fire drills. Report fire hazards immediately. Follow all workplace safety policies. Fire Prevention at Home Homeowners and family members should: Install smoke alarms. Test smoke alarms regularly. Keep emergency contact numbers accessible. Prepare a family evacuation plan. Teach children basic fire safety. Fire Prevention in Government Offices Government facilities should: Conduct regular fire safety inspections. Maintain fire extinguishers. Keep evacuation routes clear. Display emergency exit signs. Train employees on emergency response procedures. Fire Safety Checklist Before leaving your home or workplace, always check the following: ☐ Electrical appliances are turned off. • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • 3 ☐ Gas valves are closed. ☐ Fire exits are unobstructed. ☐ Flammable materials are stored properly. ☐ Smoke detectors are functioning. ☐ Fire extinguishers are accessible. Key Takeaways Most fire incidents are preventable. Safe electrical practices significantly reduce fire risks. Proper housekeeping helps eliminate fire hazards. Everyone has a role in maintaining fire safety. Prevention is always better than emergency response. Lesson Summary Fire prevention begins with awareness and responsible behavior. By identifying hazards, following safety procedures, and maintaining a clean and organized environment, individuals can greatly reduce the likelihood of fire incidents. Consistent fire prevention practices help protect lives, property, and the community. End of Lesson Proceed to Lesson 4: Fire Extinguisher Types. • • • • • 4', 'ready', NULL, '2026-07-10 06:19:34', '2026-07-10 06:19:32', '2026-07-10 06:19:34'),
	(14, 18, 'Training Content', 'text', '<h3><b>Lesson 1: Understanding Fire and Fire Emergencies</b></h3>\r\n<h2 data-section-id="qeddxq" data-start="496" data-end="514">Lesson Overview</h2>\r\n<p data-start="516" data-end="762">Fire is one of the most dangerous emergencies that can occur in homes, schools, workplaces, and communities. Within a few minutes, a small fire can grow into a life-threatening situation, causing injuries, loss of property, and even loss of life.</p>\r\n<p data-start="764" data-end="1029">Understanding how fires start, how they spread, and the risks they pose is the foundation of fire safety. Before learning how to extinguish a fire or perform an evacuation, every individual must first understand the nature of fire and recognize common fire hazards.</p>\r\n<p data-start="1031" data-end="1207">This lesson introduces the basic concepts of fire, the different classifications of fires, and the importance of early detection and immediate response during fire emergencies.</p>\r\n<hr data-start="1209" data-end="1212">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="1scsphp" data-start="1214" data-end="1236">Learning Objectives</h2>\r\n<p data-start="1238" data-end="1299">After completing this lesson, participants should be able to:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="1301" data-end="1557">\r\n<li data-section-id="xkdrzw" data-start="1301" data-end="1342">\r\nExplain what fire is and how it starts.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="2392gf" data-start="1343" data-end="1396">\r\nIdentify the three components of the Fire Triangle.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="17gltaf" data-start="1397" data-end="1440">\r\nDifferentiate the common classes of fire.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1735znt" data-start="1441" data-end="1485">\r\nRecognize common causes of fire incidents.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="4m5aiu" data-start="1486" data-end="1557">\r\nUnderstand the dangers of smoke, heat, and toxic gases during a fire.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="1559" data-end="1562">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="be9p3m" data-start="1564" data-end="1580">What is Fire?</h2>\r\n<p data-start="1582" data-end="1684">Fire is a chemical reaction called <strong data-start="1617" data-end="1631">combustion</strong>, which occurs when three essential elements combine:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="1686" data-end="1708">\r\n<li data-section-id="1j3rhkg" data-start="1686" data-end="1692">\r\nHeat\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1j45g8i" data-start="1693" data-end="1699">\r\nFuel\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1sy1ca2" data-start="1700" data-end="1708">\r\nOxygen\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p data-start="1710" data-end="1758">These three elements form the <strong data-start="1740" data-end="1757">Fire Triangle</strong>.</p>\r\n<p data-start="1760" data-end="1831">If any one of these elements is removed, the fire will be extinguished.</p>\r\n<hr data-start="1833" data-end="1836">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="12bhqcq" data-start="1838" data-end="1858">The Fire Triangle</h2>\r\n<h3 data-section-id="ynnlsu" data-start="1860" data-end="1868">Heat</h3>\r\n<p data-start="1870" data-end="1934">Heat provides the energy needed to ignite combustible materials.</p>\r\n<p data-start="1936" data-end="1945">Examples:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="1946" data-end="2023">\r\n<li data-section-id="7id11q" data-start="1946" data-end="1965">\r\nElectrical sparks\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="hhzsc" data-start="1966" data-end="1979">\r\nOpen flames\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="rj1g3d" data-start="1980" data-end="2003">\r\nHot cooking equipment\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="18raliw" data-start="2004" data-end="2023">\r\nWelding equipment\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="2025" data-end="2028">\r\n<h3 data-section-id="ynae70" data-start="2030" data-end="2038">Fuel</h3>\r\n<p data-start="2040" data-end="2087">Fuel is any combustible material that can burn.</p>\r\n<p data-start="2089" data-end="2098">Examples:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="2099" data-end="2149">\r\n<li data-section-id="1j4gel7" data-start="2099" data-end="2105">\r\nWood\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1758ake" data-start="2106" data-end="2113">\r\nPaper\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="w8sojc" data-start="2114" data-end="2123">\r\nPlastic\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1y953qt" data-start="2124" data-end="2132">\r\nFabric\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1o48ab" data-start="2133" data-end="2138">\r\nLPG\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="czkw7w" data-start="2139" data-end="2149">\r\nGasoline\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="2151" data-end="2154">\r\n<h3 data-section-id="hf6ypw" data-start="2156" data-end="2166">Oxygen</h3>\r\n<p data-start="2168" data-end="2206">Oxygen in the air supports combustion.</p>\r\n<p data-start="2208" data-end="2308">Removing oxygen (such as covering a fire with a fire blanket) can extinguish certain types of fires.</p>\r\n<hr data-start="2310" data-end="2313">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="jds6ox" data-start="2315" data-end="2340">Common Classes of Fire</h2>\r\n<h3 data-section-id="1xcae76" data-start="2342" data-end="2359">Class A Fires</h3>\r\n<p data-start="2361" data-end="2392">Ordinary combustible materials.</p>\r\n<p data-start="2394" data-end="2403">Examples:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="2404" data-end="2445">\r\n<li data-section-id="1j4gel7" data-start="2404" data-end="2410">\r\nWood\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1758ake" data-start="2411" data-end="2418">\r\nPaper\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="16xd790" data-start="2419" data-end="2426">\r\nCloth\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="6r5cfs" data-start="2427" data-end="2435">\r\nRubber\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="w8sojc" data-start="2436" data-end="2445">\r\nPlastic\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="2447" data-end="2450">\r\n<h3 data-section-id="1oz8929" data-start="2452" data-end="2469">Class B Fires</h3>\r\n<p data-start="2471" data-end="2489">Flammable liquids.</p>\r\n<p data-start="2491" data-end="2500">Examples:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="2501" data-end="2544">\r\n<li data-section-id="czkw7w" data-start="2501" data-end="2511">\r\nGasoline\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1uahxsq" data-start="2512" data-end="2520">\r\nDiesel\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1758i6i" data-start="2521" data-end="2528">\r\nPaint\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1o4b9e" data-start="2529" data-end="2534">\r\nOil\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1d73b6q" data-start="2535" data-end="2544">\r\nAlcohol\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="2546" data-end="2549">\r\n<h3 data-section-id="150wjj4" data-start="2551" data-end="2568">Class C Fires</h3>\r\n<p data-start="2570" data-end="2628">Electrical fires involving energized electrical equipment.</p>\r\n<p data-start="2630" data-end="2639">Examples:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="2640" data-end="2693">\r\n<li data-section-id="f5o9i4" data-start="2640" data-end="2651">\r\nComputers\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="7cmx5v" data-start="2652" data-end="2671">\r\nElectrical panels\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1pkapfa" data-start="2672" data-end="2684">\r\nAppliances\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="8oxauc" data-start="2685" data-end="2693">\r\nWiring\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="2695" data-end="2698">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="hfvdqf" data-start="2700" data-end="2722">Common Fire Hazards</h2>\r\n<p data-start="2724" data-end="2791">Fire hazards are conditions that increase the likelihood of a fire.</p>\r\n<p data-start="2793" data-end="2810">Examples include:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="2812" data-end="2990">\r\n<li data-section-id="dvt4fj" data-start="2812" data-end="2843">\r\nOverloaded electrical outlets\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="z7nnc5" data-start="2844" data-end="2871">\r\nDamaged electrical wiring\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="8bftno" data-start="2872" data-end="2894">\r\nImproper LPG storage\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1pb47xw" data-start="2895" data-end="2915">\r\nUnattended cooking\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="11zq8cw" data-start="2916" data-end="2933">\r\nSmoking indoors\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="dcyioe" data-start="2934" data-end="2948">\r\nOpen candles\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1prczpr" data-start="2949" data-end="2990">\r\nImproper storage of flammable materials\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="2992" data-end="2995">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="1aznwl0" data-start="2997" data-end="3022">Why Smoke is Dangerous</h2>\r\n<p data-start="3024" data-end="3098">Many fire-related deaths are caused by smoke inhalation rather than burns.</p>\r\n<p data-start="3100" data-end="3138">Smoke contains harmful gases that can:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="3140" data-end="3240">\r\n<li data-section-id="x9uhbi" data-start="3140" data-end="3159">\r\nReduce visibility\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1ff2pro" data-start="3160" data-end="3190">\r\nCause breathing difficulties\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="365sot" data-start="3191" data-end="3216">\r\nLead to unconsciousness\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="gizik1" data-start="3217" data-end="3240">\r\nResult in suffocation\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p data-start="3242" data-end="3260">During evacuation:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="3262" data-end="3343">\r\n<li data-section-id="lbd1fg" data-start="3262" data-end="3288">\r\nStay low to avoid smoke.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="ukhi4a" data-start="3289" data-end="3343">\r\nCover your nose and mouth with a cloth if necessary.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="3345" data-end="3348">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="9jfqz8" data-start="3350" data-end="3366">Key Takeaways</h2>\r\n<ul data-start="3368" data-end="3617">\r\n<li data-section-id="1rhtgtn" data-start="3368" data-end="3407">\r\nFire requires heat, fuel, and oxygen.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="ac5m30" data-start="3408" data-end="3451">\r\nFires spread rapidly when not controlled.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="hd3rgg" data-start="3452" data-end="3525">\r\nUnderstanding fire classifications helps determine the proper response.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="97clee" data-start="3526" data-end="3568">\r\nSmoke can be more dangerous than flames.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="19fzow3" data-start="3569" data-end="3617">\r\nEarly detection and quick response save lives.</li></ul>', NULL, NULL, 1, 3, 3, 'Lesson 1: Understanding Fire and Fire Emergencies Lesson Overview Fire is one of the most dangerous emergencies that can occur in homes, schools, workplaces, and communities. Within a few minutes, a small fire can grow into a life-threatening situation, causing injuries, loss of property, and even loss of life. Understanding how fires start, how they spread, and the risks they pose is the foundation of fire safety. Before learning how to extinguish a fire or perform an evacuation, every individual must first understand the nature of fire and recognize common fire hazards. This lesson introduces the basic concepts of fire, the different classifications of fires, and the importance of early detection and immediate response during fire emergencies. Learning Objectives After completing this lesson, participants should be able to: Explain what fire is and how it starts. Identify the three components of the Fire Triangle. Differentiate the common classes of fire. Recognize common causes of fire incidents. Understand the dangers of smoke, heat, and toxic gases during a fire. What is Fire? Fire is a chemical reaction called combustion, which occurs when three essential elements combine: Heat Fuel Oxygen These three elements form the Fire Triangle. If any one of these elements is removed, the fire will be extinguished. The Fire Triangle Heat Heat provides the energy needed to ignite combustible materials. Examples: Electrical sparks Open flames Hot cooking equipment Welding equipment Fuel Fuel is any combustible material that can burn. Examples: Wood Paper Plastic Fabric LPG Gasoline Oxygen Oxygen in the air supports combustion. Removing oxygen (such as covering a fire with a fire blanket) can extinguish certain types of fires. Common Classes of Fire Class A Fires Ordinary combustible materials. Examples: Wood Paper Cloth Rubber Plastic Class B Fires Flammable liquids. Examples: Gasoline Diesel Paint Oil Alcohol Class C Fires Electrical fires involving energized electrical equipment. Examples: Computers Electrical panels Appliances Wiring Common Fire Hazards Fire hazards are conditions that increase the likelihood of a fire. Examples include: Overloaded electrical outlets Damaged electrical wiring Improper LPG storage Unattended cooking Smoking indoors Open candles Improper storage of flammable materials Why Smoke is Dangerous Many fire-related deaths are caused by smoke inhalation rather than burns. Smoke contains harmful gases that can: Reduce visibility Cause breathing difficulties Lead to unconsciousness Result in suffocation During evacuation: Stay low to avoid smoke. Cover your nose and mouth with a cloth if necessary. Key Takeaways Fire requires heat, fuel, and oxygen. Fires spread rapidly when not controlled. Understanding fire classifications helps determine the proper response. Smoke can be more dangerous than flames. Early detection and quick response save lives.', 'ready', NULL, '2026-07-13 00:51:06', '2026-07-13 00:51:06', '2026-07-13 00:51:06'),
	(15, 18, 'Video', 'youtube', NULL, NULL, 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YV8TT9LRBrY', 2, 3, 3, NULL, 'not_applicable', NULL, '2026-07-13 01:01:09', '2026-07-13 00:51:07', '2026-07-13 01:01:09'),
	(16, 19, 'Training Content', 'text', '<h2 data-section-id="qeddxq" data-start="3687" data-end="3705" class="PDq2pG_selectionAnchorContainer">Lesson 2: Fire Emergency Response and Evacuation Procedures<br><br>Lesson Overview<span aria-hidden="true" class="PDq2pG_selectionAnchor"></span></h2>\r\n<p data-start="3707" data-end="3872">Knowing how to respond during a fire emergency is just as important as preventing one. Panic, confusion, and delayed decision-making can place lives at greater risk.</p>\r\n<p data-start="3874" data-end="4097">This lesson focuses on the proper actions to take when a fire occurs, including activating emergency alarms, reporting the incident, safely evacuating the area, assisting others, and following emergency response procedures.</p>\r\n<p data-start="4099" data-end="4248">Participants will also learn the importance of designated evacuation routes, assembly areas, and basic emergency communication during fire incidents.</p>\r\n<hr data-start="4250" data-end="4253">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="1scsphp" data-start="4255" data-end="4277">Learning Objectives</h2>\r\n<p data-start="4279" data-end="4340">After completing this lesson, participants should be able to:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="4342" data-end="4601">\r\n<li data-section-id="1pj50mq" data-start="4342" data-end="4397">\r\nDescribe the correct actions during a fire emergency.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="13rjhp0" data-start="4398" data-end="4436">\r\nIdentify safe evacuation procedures.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1kl1c09" data-start="4437" data-end="4484">\r\nRecognize emergency exits and assembly areas.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="sodu2e" data-start="4485" data-end="4547">\r\nExplain the importance of remaining calm during emergencies.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="8e9djo" data-start="4548" data-end="4601">\r\nUnderstand basic emergency communication protocols.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="4603" data-end="4606">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="1do645z" data-start="4608" data-end="4640">Steps During a Fire Emergency</h2>\r\n<h3 data-section-id="1cjt5b9" data-start="4642" data-end="4658">1. Stay Calm</h3>\r\n<p data-start="4660" data-end="4672">Avoid panic.</p>\r\n<p data-start="4674" data-end="4704">Think clearly and act quickly.</p>\r\n<hr data-start="4706" data-end="4709">\r\n<h3 data-section-id="1wvyxg1" data-start="4711" data-end="4741">2. Activate the Fire Alarm</h3>\r\n<p data-start="4743" data-end="4787">Notify everyone in the building immediately.</p>\r\n<p data-start="4789" data-end="4839">Early warning allows occupants to evacuate safely.</p>\r\n<hr data-start="4841" data-end="4844">\r\n<h3 data-section-id="1ojql45" data-start="4846" data-end="4878">3. Call Emergency Responders</h3>\r\n<p data-start="4880" data-end="4888">Provide:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="4890" data-end="4971">\r\n<li data-section-id="1k20mzi" data-start="4890" data-end="4906">\r\nExact location\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1co3hbt" data-start="4907" data-end="4927">\r\nNature of the fire\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1frl0h0" data-start="4928" data-end="4955">\r\nNumber of people involved\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="14fozyk" data-start="4956" data-end="4971">\r\nKnown hazards\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="4973" data-end="4976">\r\n<h3 data-section-id="lxxwvg" data-start="4978" data-end="5005">4. Evacuate Immediately</h3>\r\n<p data-start="5007" data-end="5043">Follow designated evacuation routes.</p>\r\n<p data-start="5045" data-end="5066">Do not use elevators.</p>\r\n<p data-start="5068" data-end="5150">Assist children, elderly persons, and persons with disabilities whenever possible.</p>\r\n<hr data-start="5152" data-end="5155">\r\n<h3 data-section-id="1vqysl8" data-start="5157" data-end="5192">5. Proceed to the Assembly Area</h3>\r\n<p data-start="5194" data-end="5241">Move directly to the designated assembly point.</p>\r\n<p data-start="5243" data-end="5296">Remain there until authorities declare the area safe.</p>\r\n<p data-start="5298" data-end="5359">Never return inside the building without official permission.</p>\r\n<hr data-start="5361" data-end="5364">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="ncmosh" data-start="5366" data-end="5396">Basic Evacuation Guidelines</h2>\r\n<ul data-start="5398" data-end="5564">\r\n<li data-section-id="18qhjb5" data-start="5398" data-end="5412">\r\nWalk calmly.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="g88ljl" data-start="5413" data-end="5426">\r\nDo not run.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1xau1ym" data-start="5427" data-end="5453">\r\nFollow evacuation signs.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="o3mnmv" data-start="5454" data-end="5495">\r\nStay together with your assigned group.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="b74mco" data-start="5496" data-end="5533">\r\nClose doors behind you if possible.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1lhkrwf" data-start="5534" data-end="5564">\r\nNever block emergency exits.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="5566" data-end="5569">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="1480y21" data-start="5571" data-end="5596">If You Encounter Smoke</h2>\r\n<ul data-start="5598" data-end="5687">\r\n<li data-section-id="sxsyjx" data-start="5598" data-end="5609">\r\nStay low.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="2mojwl" data-start="5610" data-end="5631">\r\nCrawl if necessary.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1jbdggd" data-start="5632" data-end="5660">\r\nCover your nose and mouth.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="118xd8x" data-start="5661" data-end="5687">\r\nAvoid opening hot doors.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="5689" data-end="5692">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="hhrhg4" data-start="5694" data-end="5723">If Your Clothes Catch Fire</h2>\r\n<p data-start="5725" data-end="5734">Remember:</p>\r\n<p data-start="5736" data-end="5758"><strong data-start="5736" data-end="5758">STOP – DROP – ROLL</strong></p>\r\n<ul data-start="5760" data-end="5838">\r\n<li data-section-id="bcbq5m" data-start="5760" data-end="5774">\r\nStop moving.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1y4ikjs" data-start="5775" data-end="5796">\r\nDrop to the ground.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="16f4dy9" data-start="5797" data-end="5838">\r\nRoll until the flames are extinguished.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="5840" data-end="5843">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="1pb5w3w" data-start="5845" data-end="5871">Emergency Communication</h2>\r\n<p data-start="5873" data-end="5947">Always provide clear and accurate information when reporting an emergency.</p>\r\n<p data-start="5949" data-end="5980">Important information includes:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="5982" data-end="6065">\r\n<li data-section-id="3ic6c5" data-start="5982" data-end="5992">\r\nLocation\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1dzvep" data-start="5993" data-end="6007">\r\nType of fire\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="19dw2jp" data-start="6008" data-end="6025">\r\nInjured persons\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="gtxyzw" data-start="6026" data-end="6045">\r\nTrapped occupants\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="o2zdxq" data-start="6046" data-end="6065">\r\nImmediate hazards\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="6067" data-end="6070">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="atnw2r" data-start="6072" data-end="6114">Common Mistakes During Fire Emergencies</h2>\r\n<p data-start="6116" data-end="6136">Avoid the following:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="6138" data-end="6292">\r\n<li data-section-id="14ddeov" data-start="6138" data-end="6173">\r\nReturning for personal belongings\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1ner49b" data-start="6174" data-end="6191">\r\nUsing elevators\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="q0x0x8" data-start="6192" data-end="6220">\r\nIgnoring evacuation alarms\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1mdi9h1" data-start="6221" data-end="6248">\r\nRunning during evacuation\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1721r4i" data-start="6249" data-end="6265">\r\nBlocking exits\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="6fsxlu" data-start="6266" data-end="6292">\r\nSpreading misinformation\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="6294" data-end="6297">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="9jfqz8" data-start="6299" data-end="6315">Key Takeaways</h2>\r\n<ul data-start="6317" data-end="6543">\r\n<li data-section-id="1mr7uws" data-start="6317" data-end="6349">\r\nStaying calm helps save lives.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="15jzlp4" data-start="6350" data-end="6396">\r\nImmediate evacuation is the safest response.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="gsmx41" data-start="6397" data-end="6427">\r\nAlways use designated exits.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="w4zgar" data-start="6428" data-end="6472">\r\nReport emergencies clearly and accurately.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="18f8ubq" data-start="6473" data-end="6543">\r\nFollow the instructions of emergency responders and safety officers.</li></ul>', NULL, NULL, 1, 3, 3, 'Lesson 2: Fire Emergency Response and Evacuation Procedures Lesson Overview Knowing how to respond during a fire emergency is just as important as preventing one. Panic, confusion, and delayed decision-making can place lives at greater risk. This lesson focuses on the proper actions to take when a fire occurs, including activating emergency alarms, reporting the incident, safely evacuating the area, assisting others, and following emergency response procedures. Participants will also learn the importance of designated evacuation routes, assembly areas, and basic emergency communication during fire incidents. Learning Objectives After completing this lesson, participants should be able to: Describe the correct actions during a fire emergency. Identify safe evacuation procedures. Recognize emergency exits and assembly areas. Explain the importance of remaining calm during emergencies. Understand basic emergency communication protocols. Steps During a Fire Emergency 1. Stay Calm Avoid panic. Think clearly and act quickly. 2. Activate the Fire Alarm Notify everyone in the building immediately. Early warning allows occupants to evacuate safely. 3. Call Emergency Responders Provide: Exact location Nature of the fire Number of people involved Known hazards 4. Evacuate Immediately Follow designated evacuation routes. Do not use elevators. Assist children, elderly persons, and persons with disabilities whenever possible. 5. Proceed to the Assembly Area Move directly to the designated assembly point. Remain there until authorities declare the area safe. Never return inside the building without official permission. Basic Evacuation Guidelines Walk calmly. Do not run. Follow evacuation signs. Stay together with your assigned group. Close doors behind you if possible. Never block emergency exits. If You Encounter Smoke Stay low. Crawl if necessary. Cover your nose and mouth. Avoid opening hot doors. If Your Clothes Catch Fire Remember: STOP – DROP – ROLL Stop moving. Drop to the ground. Roll until the flames are extinguished. Emergency Communication Always provide clear and accurate information when reporting an emergency. Important information includes: Location Type of fire Injured persons Trapped occupants Immediate hazards Common Mistakes During Fire Emergencies Avoid the following: Returning for personal belongings Using elevators Ignoring evacuation alarms Running during evacuation Blocking exits Spreading misinformation Key Takeaways Staying calm helps save lives. Immediate evacuation is the safest response. Always use designated exits. Report emergencies clearly and accurately. Follow the instructions of emergency responders and safety officers.', 'ready', NULL, '2026-07-13 00:53:53', '2026-07-13 00:53:52', '2026-07-13 00:53:53'),
	(17, 20, 'Training Content', 'text', '<h2 data-section-id="qeddxq" data-start="380" data-end="398" class="PDq2pG_selectionAnchorContainer">Lesson 4: Proper Use of Fire Extinguishers (PASS Technique)<br><br>Lesson Overview<span aria-hidden="true" class="PDq2pG_selectionAnchor"></span></h2>\r\n<p data-start="400" data-end="727">Fire extinguishers are one of the most important pieces of emergency equipment used to control small fires before they become uncontrollable. However, simply having a fire extinguisher nearby is not enough. Individuals must know when it is safe to use one, how to operate it correctly, and when evacuation is the better option.</p>\r\n<p data-start="729" data-end="962">This lesson introduces the different types of fire extinguishers, explains which fires they are designed to extinguish, and teaches the internationally recognized <strong data-start="892" data-end="910">PASS Technique</strong> for safe and effective fire extinguisher operation.</p>\r\n<hr data-start="964" data-end="967">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="1scsphp" data-start="969" data-end="991">Learning Objectives</h2>\r\n<p data-start="993" data-end="1054">After completing this lesson, participants should be able to:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="1056" data-end="1346">\r\n<li data-section-id="e62pny" data-start="1056" data-end="1109">\r\nIdentify the different types of fire extinguishers.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1ddkfh4" data-start="1110" data-end="1173">\r\nMatch the correct extinguisher to the appropriate fire class.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1v36ij4" data-start="1174" data-end="1214">\r\nDemonstrate the proper PASS Technique.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="dxkcf5" data-start="1215" data-end="1285">\r\nRecognize situations where using a fire extinguisher is appropriate.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="16aqfns" data-start="1286" data-end="1346">\r\nUnderstand when immediate evacuation is the safest option.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="1348" data-end="1351">\r\n<h1 data-section-id="17y991e" data-start="1353" data-end="1391">Why Fire Extinguishers are Important</h1>\r\n<p data-start="1393" data-end="1573">Fire extinguishers are designed to suppress <strong data-start="1437" data-end="1466">small, controllable fires</strong> during their early stages. Quick and proper use can prevent minor incidents from becoming major disasters.</p>\r\n<p data-start="1575" data-end="1729">However, if the fire grows rapidly, spreads to multiple areas, or produces excessive smoke, personal safety should always take priority over firefighting.</p>\r\n<hr data-start="1731" data-end="1734">\r\n<h1 data-section-id="d86tli" data-start="1736" data-end="1765">Types of Fire Extinguishers</h1>\r\n<h3 data-section-id="1pwytg2" data-start="1767" data-end="1794">Water Fire Extinguisher</h3>\r\n<p data-start="1796" data-end="1809">Suitable for:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="1811" data-end="1826">\r\n<li data-section-id="xh9pxo" data-start="1811" data-end="1826">\r\nClass A Fires\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p data-start="1828" data-end="1837">Examples:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="1839" data-end="1873">\r\n<li data-section-id="1j4gel7" data-start="1839" data-end="1845">\r\nWood\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1758ake" data-start="1846" data-end="1853">\r\nPaper\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="16xd790" data-start="1854" data-end="1861">\r\nCloth\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="14z5qli" data-start="1862" data-end="1873">\r\nCardboard\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p data-start="1875" data-end="1930"><strong data-start="1875" data-end="1930">Do NOT use on electrical or flammable liquid fires.</strong></p>\r\n<hr data-start="1932" data-end="1935">\r\n<h3 data-section-id="57q5fb" data-start="1937" data-end="1966">Dry Chemical Powder (ABC)</h3>\r\n<p data-start="1968" data-end="1981">Suitable for:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="1983" data-end="2012">\r\n<li data-section-id="91bhpj" data-start="1983" data-end="1992">\r\nClass A\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="91bhpg" data-start="1993" data-end="2002">\r\nClass B\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="91bhph" data-start="2003" data-end="2012">\r\nClass C\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p data-start="2014" data-end="2130">Commonly found in schools, offices, homes, and government facilities because it is suitable for multiple fire types.</p>\r\n<hr data-start="2132" data-end="2135">\r\n<h3 data-section-id="67j7s8" data-start="2137" data-end="2161">Carbon Dioxide (CO₂)</h3>\r\n<p data-start="2163" data-end="2176">Suitable for:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="2178" data-end="2221">\r\n<li data-section-id="2lzo6l" data-start="2178" data-end="2196">\r\nElectrical Fires\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="4mb166" data-start="2197" data-end="2221">\r\nFlammable Liquid Fires\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p data-start="2223" data-end="2323">Leaves no residue, making it ideal for protecting computers, electrical equipment, and server rooms.</p>\r\n<hr data-start="2325" data-end="2328">\r\n<h3 data-section-id="qiuzgi" data-start="2330" data-end="2356">Foam Fire Extinguisher</h3>\r\n<p data-start="2358" data-end="2371">Suitable for:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="2373" data-end="2398">\r\n<li data-section-id="91bhpj" data-start="2373" data-end="2382">\r\nClass A\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1y356rz" data-start="2383" data-end="2398">\r\nClass B Fires\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p data-start="2400" data-end="2473">Effective against flammable liquids while also cooling burning materials.</p>\r\n<hr data-start="2475" data-end="2478">\r\n<h1 data-section-id="ibz0gp" data-start="2480" data-end="2514">Before Using a Fire Extinguisher</h1>\r\n<p data-start="2516" data-end="2536">Always ask yourself:</p>\r\n<p data-start="2538" data-end="2564">✔ Is the fire still small?</p>\r\n<p data-start="2566" data-end="2609">✔ Is there a clear escape route behind you?</p>\r\n<p data-start="2611" data-end="2655">✔ Has the fire alarm already been activated?</p>\r\n<p data-start="2657" data-end="2699">✔ Have emergency responders been notified?</p>\r\n<p data-start="2701" data-end="2743">✔ Do you know how to use the extinguisher?</p>\r\n<p data-start="2745" data-end="2857">If the answer to any of these questions is <strong data-start="2788" data-end="2794">No</strong>, evacuate immediately instead of attempting to fight the fire.</p>\r\n<hr data-start="2859" data-end="2862">\r\n<h1 data-section-id="kuvhn6" data-start="2864" data-end="2884">The PASS Technique</h1>\r\n<p data-start="2886" data-end="2978">The PASS Technique is the internationally accepted method for operating a fire extinguisher.</p>\r\n<h3 data-section-id="1hr1hex" data-start="2980" data-end="3000">P — Pull the Pin</h3>\r\n<p data-start="3002" data-end="3051">Remove the safety pin to unlock the extinguisher.</p>\r\n<hr data-start="3053" data-end="3056">\r\n<h3 data-section-id="impdyu" data-start="3058" data-end="3069">A — Aim</h3>\r\n<p data-start="3071" data-end="3133">Aim the nozzle at the <strong data-start="3093" data-end="3113">base of the fire</strong>, not at the flames.</p>\r\n<hr data-start="3135" data-end="3138">\r\n<h3 data-section-id="fprpft" data-start="3140" data-end="3155">S — Squeeze</h3>\r\n<p data-start="3157" data-end="3218">Firmly squeeze the handle to release the extinguishing agent.</p>\r\n<hr data-start="3220" data-end="3223">\r\n<h3 data-section-id="rh0xzp" data-start="3225" data-end="3238">S — Sweep</h3>\r\n<p data-start="3240" data-end="3354">Move the nozzle slowly from side to side while aiming at the base of the fire until it is completely extinguished.</p>\r\n<p data-start="3356" data-end="3411">Continue observing the area in case the fire reignites.</p>\r\n<hr data-start="3413" data-end="3416">\r\n<h1 data-section-id="wewizl" data-start="3418" data-end="3446">Important Safety Reminders</h1>\r\n<ul data-start="3448" data-end="3703">\r\n<li data-section-id="ytkar0" data-start="3448" data-end="3481">\r\nAlways keep an exit behind you.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="2wf1pn" data-start="3482" data-end="3517">\r\nNever turn your back on the fire.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="y5ml3q" data-start="3518" data-end="3557">\r\nStop immediately if the fire spreads.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="8g7jjy" data-start="3558" data-end="3596">\r\nNever use water on electrical fires.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="d7mzru" data-start="3597" data-end="3646">\r\nDo not fight fires larger than your capability.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="h59qnq" data-start="3647" data-end="3703">\r\nLeave the area immediately if smoke becomes excessive.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="3705" data-end="3708">\r\n<h1 data-section-id="s2zwpg" data-start="3710" data-end="3727">Common Mistakes</h1>\r\n<p data-start="3729" data-end="3758">Avoid the following mistakes:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="3760" data-end="4005">\r\n<li data-section-id="jb0ohe" data-start="3760" data-end="3793">\r\nStanding too close to the fire.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1mdys8q" data-start="3794" data-end="3837">\r\nAiming at the flames instead of the base.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1lg787y" data-start="3838" data-end="3874">\r\nPulling the trigger before aiming.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1e9v84m" data-start="3875" data-end="3904">\r\nBlocking your escape route.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1bztgsy" data-start="3905" data-end="3944">\r\nUsing the wrong type of extinguisher.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1l08jwh" data-start="3945" data-end="4005">\r\nContinuing to fight a fire that is already out of control.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="4007" data-end="4010">\r\n<h1 data-section-id="19z231s" data-start="4012" data-end="4037">Practical Demonstration</h1>\r\n<p data-start="4039" data-end="4113">Participants should practice the following during the simulation exercise:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="4115" data-end="4344">\r\n<li data-section-id="1uigqcy" data-start="4115" data-end="4158">\r\nInspect the fire extinguisher before use.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="v50bi1" data-start="4159" data-end="4193">\r\nRemove the safety pin correctly.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="2fp8hv" data-start="4194" data-end="4223">\r\nPerform the PASS Technique.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="py3w0r" data-start="4224" data-end="4265">\r\nMaintain a safe distance from the fire.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="dgyldb" data-start="4266" data-end="4309">\r\nExtinguish the simulated fire completely.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1wlfgaf" data-start="4310" data-end="4344">\r\nReturn to a safe area after use.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="4346" data-end="4349">\r\n<h1 data-section-id="1xv8ueh" data-start="4351" data-end="4375">Real-World Application</h1>\r\n<p data-start="4377" data-end="4697">During community fire safety drills, participants may be asked to extinguish a controlled training fire using a fire extinguisher under the supervision of a certified trainer. This practical activity helps participants build confidence and develop the skills needed to respond effectively during actual fire emergencies.</p>\r\n<hr data-start="4699" data-end="4702">\r\n<h1 data-section-id="1bcdnav" data-start="4704" data-end="4719">Key Takeaways</h1>\r\n<ul data-start="4721" data-end="5119">\r\n<li data-section-id="hrbwt8" data-start="4721" data-end="4789">\r\nAlways identify the type of fire before using a fire extinguisher.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="n044xb" data-start="4790" data-end="4849">\r\nUse the correct extinguisher for the specific fire class.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1fphf1" data-start="4850" data-end="5016">\r\nRemember the <strong data-start="4865" data-end="4883">PASS Technique</strong>:\r\n<ul data-start="4887" data-end="5016">\r\n<li data-section-id="xt40rk" data-start="4887" data-end="4909">\r\n<strong data-start="4889" data-end="4894">P</strong> – Pull the Pin\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="iz85ta" data-start="4912" data-end="4949">\r\n<strong data-start="4914" data-end="4919">A</strong> – Aim at the base of the fire\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1eb437" data-start="4952" data-end="4980">\r\n<strong data-start="4954" data-end="4959">S</strong> – Squeeze the handle\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="762d2p" data-start="4983" data-end="5016">\r\n<strong data-start="4985" data-end="4990">S</strong> – Sweep from side to side\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="fh9bhr" data-start="5017" data-end="5075">\r\nNever attempt to fight large or rapidly spreading fires.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="16nr7ic" data-start="5076" data-end="5119">\r\nPersonal safety should always come first.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3 data-section-id="ek4nr2" data-start="5126" data-end="5164"><br></h3>', NULL, NULL, 1, 3, 3, 'Lesson 4: Proper Use of Fire Extinguishers (PASS Technique) Lesson Overview Fire extinguishers are one of the most important pieces of emergency equipment used to control small fires before they become uncontrollable. However, simply having a fire extinguisher nearby is not enough. Individuals must know when it is safe to use one, how to operate it correctly, and when evacuation is the better option. This lesson introduces the different types of fire extinguishers, explains which fires they are designed to extinguish, and teaches the internationally recognized PASS Technique for safe and effective fire extinguisher operation. Learning Objectives After completing this lesson, participants should be able to: Identify the different types of fire extinguishers. Match the correct extinguisher to the appropriate fire class. Demonstrate the proper PASS Technique. Recognize situations where using a fire extinguisher is appropriate. Understand when immediate evacuation is the safest option. Why Fire Extinguishers are Important Fire extinguishers are designed to suppress small, controllable fires during their early stages. Quick and proper use can prevent minor incidents from becoming major disasters. However, if the fire grows rapidly, spreads to multiple areas, or produces excessive smoke, personal safety should always take priority over firefighting. Types of Fire Extinguishers Water Fire Extinguisher Suitable for: Class A Fires Examples: Wood Paper Cloth Cardboard Do NOT use on electrical or flammable liquid fires. Dry Chemical Powder (ABC) Suitable for: Class A Class B Class C Commonly found in schools, offices, homes, and government facilities because it is suitable for multiple fire types. Carbon Dioxide (CO₂) Suitable for: Electrical Fires Flammable Liquid Fires Leaves no residue, making it ideal for protecting computers, electrical equipment, and server rooms. Foam Fire Extinguisher Suitable for: Class A Class B Fires Effective against flammable liquids while also cooling burning materials. Before Using a Fire Extinguisher Always ask yourself: ✔ Is the fire still small? ✔ Is there a clear escape route behind you? ✔ Has the fire alarm already been activated? ✔ Have emergency responders been notified? ✔ Do you know how to use the extinguisher? If the answer to any of these questions is No, evacuate immediately instead of attempting to fight the fire. The PASS Technique The PASS Technique is the internationally accepted method for operating a fire extinguisher. P — Pull the Pin Remove the safety pin to unlock the extinguisher. A — Aim Aim the nozzle at the base of the fire, not at the flames. S — Squeeze Firmly squeeze the handle to release the extinguishing agent. S — Sweep Move the nozzle slowly from side to side while aiming at the base of the fire until it is completely extinguished. Continue observing the area in case the fire reignites. Important Safety Reminders Always keep an exit behind you. Never turn your back on the fire. Stop immediately if the fire spreads. Never use water on electrical fires. Do not fight fires larger than your capability. Leave the area immediately if smoke becomes excessive. Common Mistakes Avoid the following mistakes: Standing too close to the fire. Aiming at the flames instead of the base. Pulling the trigger before aiming. Blocking your escape route. Using the wrong type of extinguisher. Continuing to fight a fire that is already out of control. Practical Demonstration Participants should practice the following during the simulation exercise: Inspect the fire extinguisher before use. Remove the safety pin correctly. Perform the PASS Technique. Maintain a safe distance from the fire. Extinguish the simulated fire completely. Return to a safe area after use. Real-World Application During community fire safety drills, participants may be asked to extinguish a controlled training fire using a fire extinguisher under the supervision of a certified trainer. This practical activity helps participants build confidence and develop the skills needed to respond effectively during actual fire emergencies. Key Takeaways Always identify the type of fire before using a fire extinguisher. Use the correct extinguisher for the specific fire class. Remember the PASS Technique: P – Pull the Pin A – Aim at the base of the fire S – Squeeze the handle S – Sweep from side to side Never attempt to fight large or rapidly spreading fires. Personal safety should always come first.', 'ready', NULL, '2026-07-13 00:55:24', '2026-07-13 00:55:24', '2026-07-13 00:55:24'),
	(18, 21, 'Training Content', 'text', '<h1 data-section-id="pq6jyx" data-start="816" data-end="867" class="PDq2pG_selectionAnchorContainer">Lesson 5: Basic First Aid During Fire Emergencies<span aria-hidden="true" class="PDq2pG_selectionAnchor"></span></h1>\r\n<h2 data-section-id="qeddxq" data-start="869" data-end="887">Lesson Overview</h2>\r\n<p data-start="889" data-end="1176">During fire emergencies, injuries such as burns, smoke inhalation, cuts, and minor trauma can occur before emergency responders arrive. Providing proper first aid during the first few minutes after an incident can help reduce the severity of injuries and improve the chances of recovery.</p>\r\n<p data-start="1178" data-end="1379">This lesson introduces participants to the basic principles of first aid, proper treatment of common fire-related injuries, and the importance of seeking professional medical assistance when necessary.</p>\r\n<hr data-start="1381" data-end="1384">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="1scsphp" data-start="1386" data-end="1408">Learning Objectives</h2>\r\n<p data-start="1410" data-end="1471">After completing this lesson, participants should be able to:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="1473" data-end="1719">\r\n<li data-section-id="g38xxj" data-start="1473" data-end="1535">\r\nExplain the importance of first aid during fire emergencies.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="txkc27" data-start="1536" data-end="1579">\r\nIdentify common injuries caused by fires.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1aopz8q" data-start="1580" data-end="1620">\r\nApply basic first aid for minor burns.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="xiu4y" data-start="1621" data-end="1663">\r\nRecognize the signs of smoke inhalation.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1bq86tl" data-start="1664" data-end="1719">\r\nUnderstand when to seek immediate medical assistance.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="1721" data-end="1724">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="fkrf18" data-start="1726" data-end="1747">What is First Aid?</h2>\r\n<p data-start="1749" data-end="1859">First aid is the immediate care provided to an injured or ill person before professional medical help arrives.</p>\r\n<p data-start="1861" data-end="1878">Its goals are to:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="1880" data-end="1958">\r\n<li data-section-id="zjnouo" data-start="1880" data-end="1896">\r\nPreserve life.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1hytuvi" data-start="1897" data-end="1938">\r\nPrevent the injury from becoming worse.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="10oj7bv" data-start="1939" data-end="1958">\r\nPromote recovery.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="1960" data-end="1963">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="1ub04ef" data-start="1965" data-end="1996">Common Fire-Related Injuries</h2>\r\n<p data-start="1998" data-end="2029">Fire emergencies may result in:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="2031" data-end="2144">\r\n<li data-section-id="w4t83r" data-start="2031" data-end="2044">\r\nMinor burns\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1huxwl0" data-start="2045" data-end="2060">\r\nSerious burns\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="10uvbvs" data-start="2061" data-end="2079">\r\nSmoke inhalation\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1j30a7e" data-start="2080" data-end="2100">\r\nCuts and abrasions\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="11txnom" data-start="2101" data-end="2126">\r\nFalls during evacuation\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1kdgiim" data-start="2127" data-end="2144">\r\nHeat exhaustion\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="2146" data-end="2149">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="n8xvz0" data-start="2151" data-end="2174">Treating Minor Burns</h2>\r\n<p data-start="2176" data-end="2192">For minor burns:</p>\r\n<ol data-start="2194" data-end="2437">\r\n<li data-section-id="4ljt2s" data-start="2194" data-end="2239">\r\nMove the victim away from the heat source.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="kt9ztj" data-start="2240" data-end="2313">\r\nCool the burned area under cool running water for at least 20 minutes.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="ehwfg5" data-start="2314" data-end="2376">\r\nRemove jewelry or tight clothing near the burn if possible.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="koyeof" data-start="2377" data-end="2437">\r\nCover the burn with a clean, sterile, non-stick dressing.\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p data-start="2439" data-end="2452">Do not apply:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="2454" data-end="2547">\r\n<li data-section-id="1b79hsj" data-start="2454" data-end="2466">\r\nToothpaste\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1w1riaw" data-start="2467" data-end="2475">\r\nButter\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1o49fr" data-start="2476" data-end="2481">\r\nIce\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1iek8y2" data-start="2482" data-end="2495">\r\nCooking oil\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="anfavb" data-start="2496" data-end="2547">\r\nOintments unless advised by medical professionals\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="2549" data-end="2552">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="ydkf5x" data-start="2554" data-end="2573">Smoke Inhalation</h2>\r\n<p data-start="2575" data-end="2640">Smoke inhalation can be dangerous even when no burns are visible.</p>\r\n<p data-start="2642" data-end="2663">Common signs include:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="2665" data-end="2782">\r\n<li data-section-id="vec78z" data-start="2665" data-end="2687">\r\nDifficulty breathing\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1poavln" data-start="2688" data-end="2709">\r\nPersistent coughing\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1btwvc7" data-start="2710" data-end="2721">\r\nDizziness\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1s6kozz" data-start="2722" data-end="2732">\r\nHeadache\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1tbxelv" data-start="2733" data-end="2770">\r\nBlack soot around the nose or mouth\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="7ollc2" data-start="2771" data-end="2782">\r\nConfusion\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p data-start="2784" data-end="2852">Move the person to fresh air immediately and seek medical attention.</p>\r\n<hr data-start="2854" data-end="2857">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="ognucl" data-start="2859" data-end="2887">Helping an Injured Person</h2>\r\n<p data-start="2889" data-end="2913">Before giving first aid:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="2915" data-end="3050">\r\n<li data-section-id="1guggm1" data-start="2915" data-end="2941">\r\nEnsure the area is safe.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1blbbdm" data-start="2942" data-end="2967">\r\nProtect yourself first.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="vkflui" data-start="2968" data-end="2980">\r\nStay calm.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1kaay8l" data-start="2981" data-end="3011">\r\nReassure the injured person.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1vq3q2k" data-start="3012" data-end="3050">\r\nCall emergency responders if needed.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="3052" data-end="3055">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="4xzddb" data-start="3057" data-end="3091">When to Call Emergency Services</h2>\r\n<p data-start="3093" data-end="3145">Immediately seek professional medical assistance if:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="3147" data-end="3344">\r\n<li data-section-id="fu7mak" data-start="3147" data-end="3173">\r\nBurns are large or deep.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="yhhmjf" data-start="3174" data-end="3225">\r\nBurns involve the face, hands, feet, or genitals.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="i6z7vw" data-start="3226" data-end="3259">\r\nThe victim loses consciousness.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="ric3de" data-start="3260" data-end="3298">\r\nThe victim has difficulty breathing.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="eex1ov" data-start="3299" data-end="3344">\r\nThe fire involved chemicals or electricity.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="3346" data-end="3349">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="uivmt5" data-start="3351" data-end="3378">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>\r\n<p data-start="3380" data-end="3387">Do not:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="3389" data-end="3546">\r\n<li data-section-id="y0urfx" data-start="3389" data-end="3404">\r\nPop blisters.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1niw9tl" data-start="3405" data-end="3427">\r\nApply home remedies.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="v2w7aj" data-start="3428" data-end="3475">\r\nMove seriously injured victims unnecessarily.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="11tvq4j" data-start="3476" data-end="3508">\r\nIgnore breathing difficulties.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1hc12kt" data-start="3509" data-end="3546">\r\nDelay calling emergency responders.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="3548" data-end="3551">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="1pypqxn" data-start="3553" data-end="3574">Practical Activity</h2>\r\n<p data-start="3576" data-end="3605">Participants should practice:</p>\r\n<ul data-start="3607" data-end="3802">\r\n<li data-section-id="yr1b40" data-start="3607" data-end="3632">\r\nAssessing scene safety.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="eo03ut" data-start="3633" data-end="3666">\r\nTreating simulated minor burns.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1g9kmde" data-start="3667" data-end="3696">\r\nApplying sterile dressings.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="wqix12" data-start="3697" data-end="3734">\r\nAssisting smoke inhalation victims.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="duhkjp" data-start="3735" data-end="3802">\r\nCalling emergency responders using correct emergency information.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr data-start="3804" data-end="3807">\r\n<h2 data-section-id="9jfqz8" data-start="3809" data-end="3825">Key Takeaways</h2>\r\n<ul data-start="3827" data-end="4067">\r\n<li data-section-id="uhumuk" data-start="3827" data-end="3894">\r\nFirst aid helps reduce injuries before professional help arrives.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="1d7yk53" data-start="3895" data-end="3936">\r\nCool burns with running water, not ice.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="f2o89r" data-start="3937" data-end="3985">\r\nSmoke inhalation requires immediate attention.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="imckp4" data-start="3986" data-end="4019">\r\nAlways prioritize scene safety.\r\n</li>\r\n<li data-section-id="hxbyex" data-start="4020" data-end="4067">\r\nSeek medical assistance for serious injuries.</li></ul>', NULL, NULL, 1, 3, 3, 'Lesson 5: Basic First Aid During Fire Emergencies Lesson Overview During fire emergencies, injuries such as burns, smoke inhalation, cuts, and minor trauma can occur before emergency responders arrive. Providing proper first aid during the first few minutes after an incident can help reduce the severity of injuries and improve the chances of recovery. This lesson introduces participants to the basic principles of first aid, proper treatment of common fire-related injuries, and the importance of seeking professional medical assistance when necessary. Learning Objectives After completing this lesson, participants should be able to: Explain the importance of first aid during fire emergencies. Identify common injuries caused by fires. Apply basic first aid for minor burns. Recognize the signs of smoke inhalation. Understand when to seek immediate medical assistance. What is First Aid? First aid is the immediate care provided to an injured or ill person before professional medical help arrives. Its goals are to: Preserve life. Prevent the injury from becoming worse. Promote recovery. Common Fire-Related Injuries Fire emergencies may result in: Minor burns Serious burns Smoke inhalation Cuts and abrasions Falls during evacuation Heat exhaustion Treating Minor Burns For minor burns: Move the victim away from the heat source. Cool the burned area under cool running water for at least 20 minutes. Remove jewelry or tight clothing near the burn if possible. Cover the burn with a clean, sterile, non-stick dressing. Do not apply: Toothpaste Butter Ice Cooking oil Ointments unless advised by medical professionals Smoke Inhalation Smoke inhalation can be dangerous even when no burns are visible. Common signs include: Difficulty breathing Persistent coughing Dizziness Headache Black soot around the nose or mouth Confusion Move the person to fresh air immediately and seek medical attention. Helping an Injured Person Before giving first aid: Ensure the area is safe. Protect yourself first. Stay calm. Reassure the injured person. Call emergency responders if needed. When to Call Emergency Services Immediately seek professional medical assistance if: Burns are large or deep. Burns involve the face, hands, feet, or genitals. The victim loses consciousness. The victim has difficulty breathing. The fire involved chemicals or electricity. Common Mistakes to Avoid Do not: Pop blisters. Apply home remedies. Move seriously injured victims unnecessarily. Ignore breathing difficulties. Delay calling emergency responders. Practical Activity Participants should practice: Assessing scene safety. Treating simulated minor burns. Applying sterile dressings. Assisting smoke inhalation victims. Calling emergency responders using correct emergency information. Key Takeaways First aid helps reduce injuries before professional help arrives. Cool burns with running water, not ice. Smoke inhalation requires immediate attention. Always prioritize scene safety. Seek medical assistance for serious injuries.', 'ready', NULL, '2026-07-13 00:56:35', '2026-07-13 00:56:34', '2026-07-13 00:56:35');
